<MainLayout title="Understanding the GPS process in Australia | IKAI Insights" description="Understanding the GPS process in Australia">
  <section class="page-hero"><div class="container"><span class="eyebrow light">IKAI Insight</span><h1>Understanding the GPS process in Australia</h1><p class="lead">Practical perspectives from IKAI Energy Consulting.</p></div></section>
  <section class="section"><article class="container prose">
    <p>Generator Performance Standards define how a generating system is expected to perform when connected to the National Electricity Market.</p><h2>More than a compliance document</h2><p>The GPS process connects technical capability, modelling evidence, network requirements and project design. It influences equipment selection, control settings, plant testing and operational obligations.</p><h2>Start with the performance envelope</h2><p>Project teams should understand where automatic access standards are achievable, where negotiated standards may be required and what supporting evidence will be needed.</p><h2>Models and studies must tell the same story</h2><p>RMS and EMT models, study reports, design assumptions and proposed standards should remain aligned. Inconsistency creates avoidable technical queries and delays.</p><h2>Engagement matters</h2><p>A successful GPS process usually depends on clear coordination between the proponent, OEMs, consultants, the connecting NSP and AEMO.</p><p>The strongest approach is to treat GPS development as a design and delivery process — not simply a document submission.</p>
